<BODY><!-- Heading -->
<DIV id=3Dheader>
<H1><A href=3D"http://www.robweir.com/blog/">An Antic Disposition =
</A></H1>
<P id=3Ddescription>Rob Weir, thinking the unthinkable, pondering the=20
imponderable, effing the ineffable and scruting the =
inscrutable</P></DIV><!-- Main Column -->
<DIV id=3DmainClm><!-- Blog Posts -->
<H3>Tuesday, March 18, 2008</H3><A name=3D4871700534128679752></A>
<H2>How many defects remain in OOXML?</H2>
<DIV class=3DblogPost>
<DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>DIS 29500, Office Open XML, was =
submitted for=20
Fast Track review by Ecma as 6,045 page specification. (After the BRM, =
it is now=20
longer, maybe 7,500 pages or so. We don't know for sure, since the =
post-BRM text=20
is not yet available for inspection.) Based on the original 6,045 page =
length, a=20
5-month review by JTC1 NB's lead to 48 defect reports by NB's, reporting =
a total=20
of 3,522 defects. Ecma responded to these defect reports with 1,027 =
proposals,=20
which the recent BRM, mainly through the actions of one big overnight =
ballot,=20
approved.<BR><BR>So what was the initial quality of OOXML, coming into =
JTC1? One=20
measure is the defect density, which we can say is at least one defect =
for every=20
6045/1027 =3D 5.8 pages. I say "at least" because this is the lower =
bounds. If we=20
believed that the 5-month review represented a complete review of the =
text of=20
DIS 29500, by those with relevant subject matter expertise, then we =
would have=20
some confidence that all, or at least most, defects were detected, =
reported and=20
repaired. But I don't know anyone who really thinks the 5-month review =
was=20
sufficient for a technical review of 6,045 pages. Further, we know that=20
Microsoft worked actively to suppress the reporting of defects by NB's. =
So the=20
actual defect density is potentially quite a bit higher than the =
reported defect=20
density.<BR><BR>But how much higher? This is the important question. It =
doesn't=20
matter how many defects were fixed. What matters is how many=20
remain.<BR><BR>There are several approaches to answering this question. =
One=20
approach is to look at defect "find rates", the number of defects found =
per unit=20
of time spent reviewing, and fit that to a model, typical an S-curve =
(sigmoid)=20
and use that model to predict the number of defects remaining. However, =
we have=20
no time/effort data for the DIS 29500 review, so we don't have enough =
data to=20
create that model. Another approach is to randomly sample the post-BRM =
text and=20
statistically estimate the defect density by this sample.<BR><BR>Are =
there any=20
other good approaches?<BR><BR>Here is the plan. I will use the second =
approach.=20
Since I do not actually have the post-BRM text, I need to make some =
adjustments.=20
I'll start with the original text, in particular Part 4, the XML =
reference=20
section, at 5,220 pages, where the meat of the standard is. I'll then =
create a=20
spreadsheet and generate 200 random page numbers between 1 and 5,220. =
For each=20
random page I will review the clause associated with that page and note =
the=20
technical and editorial errors I find. I will then check these errors to =
see if=20
any of them were addressed by BRM resolutions.<BR><BR>Based on the =
above, I will=20
be able to estimate two numbers:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>The defect density of the text, both pre and post BRM
  <LI>The fraction of defects which were detected by the Fast Track=20
  review.<BR></LI></UL>So if I find N defects, and 0.9N of those issues =
were=20
already found during the Fast Track review and were addressed by the =
BRM, then=20
we can say that the Fast Track procedure was 90% effective in finding =
and=20
removing errors. Some practitioners would call that the defect removal =
"yield"=20
of the process. But if we find that only 0.1N of the errors were =
reported and=20
addressed by the BRM, then we'll have a different opinion on the =
sufficiency of=20
the Fast Track review.<BR><BR>Clear enough? Microsoft is claiming =
something like=20
99% of all issues were resolved at the BRM. So let's see if we get =
anything=20
close.<BR><BR>I'm not done with this study yet. I'm finding so many =
defects that=20
recording them is taking more time than finding them. But since this is =
topical,=20
I will report what I have found so far, based on the first 25 random =
pages, or=20
1/8th completion of my target 200. I've found 64 technical flaws. None =
of the 64=20
flaws were addressed by the BRM. Among the defects are some rather =
serious ones=20
such as:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>storage of plain text passwords in database connection strings
  <LI>Undefined mappings between CSS and DrawingML
  <LI>Errors in XML Schema definitions
  <LI>Dependencies of proprietary Microsoft Internet Explorer features
  <LI>Spreadsheet functions that break with non-Latin characters
  <LI>Dependencies on Microsoft OLE method calls
  <LI>Numerous undefined terms and features</LI></UL>As I said, this =
study is=20
still underway. I'll list the defects I've found so far, and add to it =
as I=20
complete the task over the next few days.<BR>
<OL>
  <LI>Page 692, Section 2.7.3.13 =E2=80=94 no errors found
  <LI>Page 1457, Section 2.15.3.45 =E2=80=94 This is a compatibility =
setting which=20
  creates needless complexity for implementers who now must deal with =
two=20
  different ways of handling a page break, one in which a page break =
ends the=20
  current paragraph, and another where it does not. This is not a =
general need=20
  and expresses only a single vendor=E2=80=99s legacy setting.
  <LI>Page 490, Section 2.4.72 =E2=80=94 This defines the ST_TblWidth =
type, used to=20
  express the width of a table column, cell spacing, margins, etc. The =
allowed=20
  values of this type express the measurement units to be used: Auto, =
Twentieths=20
  of a point, Nil (no width), Fiftieths of a percent. I find these =
choices to be=20
  capricious and not based on any sound engineering principle. It also =
mixes=20
  units with width values (Nil) and modes (auto). This should be changed =
to=20
  allow measurements in natural units, such as allowed in XSL-FO or =
CSS2, such=20
  as mm, inches, points, pica. Also, do not mix units, values and modes =
in the=20
  same attribute. Nil is best represented by the value 0 and Auto should =
be its=20
  own Boolean attribute.
  <LI>Page 328, Section 2.4.17 =E2=80=94 The frame attribute description =
says it=20
  =E2=80=9CSpecifies whether the specified border should be modified to =
create a frame=20
  effect by reversing the border's appearance from the edge nearest the =
text to=20
  the edge furthest from the text.=E2=80=9D This is not clear. What does =
it mean to=20
  reverse a border=E2=80=99s appearance? Are we doing color inversions? =
Flipping along=20
  the Y-axis? What exactly? Also a typographical error: =E2=80=9CFor the =
right and top=20
  borders, this is accomplished by moving the order down and to the =
right of its=20
  original location.=E2=80=9D Should be =E2=80=9Cmoving the border =
down=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D Also, it is not stated=20
  how far the border should be moved.<BR>
  <LI>Page 1073, Section 2.14.8 =E2=80=94 This feature is described as: =
=E2=80=9CThis element=20
  specifies the connection string used to reconnect to an external data =
source.=20
  The string within this element's val attribute shall contain the =
connection=20
  string that the hosting application shall pass to a external data =
source=20
  access application to enable the WordprocessingML document to be =
reconnected=20
  to the specified external data source.=E2=80=9D Since connection to =
external data=20
  typically requires a user ID and a password, the lack of any security=20
  mechanism on this feature is alarming. The example given in the text =
itself=20
  hardcodes a plain-text password in it the connection string.<BR>
  <LI>Page 4387, Section 6.1.2.3 =E2=80=94 For the =
=E2=80=9Cclass=E2=80=9D attribute it says =E2=80=9CSpecifies=20
  a reference to the definition of a CSS style.=E2=80=9D The example =
implies that some=20
  sort of mapping will occur between CSS attributes and DrawingML. But =
no such=20
  mapping is defined in OOXML. The "doubleclicknotify" attribute implies =
some=20
  sort of event model that us undefined in OOXML. How do you send a =
message for=20
  doubleclicknotify? Why do we describe organization chart layouts here =
when it=20
  is not applicable to a bezier curve? What happens if this shape is =
declared to=20
  be a horizontal rule or bullet or ole object? The text allows you =
label it as=20
  one of these, but assigns no meaning or behavior to this. Why do we =
have an=20
  spid as well as an id attribute? The "target" attribute refers to=20
  Microsoft-specific I.E. features such as "_media". Although the text =
says that=20
  control points have default values, the schema fragment does not show =
this.
  <LI>Page 3164, Section 4.6.88 =E2=80=94 This and the following two =
elements are all=20
  called "To" but this seems to be a naming error. 4.6.89 is essentially =

  undefined. What does "The element specifies the certain attribute of a =
time=20
  node after an animation effect" mean? It doesn't seem to really =
signify=20
  anything. Ditto for 4.6.90.<BR>
  <LI>Page 5098, Section 7.1.2.124 =E2=80=94 The example does not =
illustrate what the=20
  text claims it does. The example doesn't even use the element defined =
by this=20
  clause.<BR>
  <LI>Page 4492, Section 6.1.2.11 =E2=80=94 The "althref" attribute is =
described as=20
  "Defines an alternate reference for an image in Macintosh PICT =
format". Why is=20
  this necessary for only Mac PICT files? Why would "bilevel" =
necessarily lead=20
  to 8 colors? We're well beyond 8-bit color these days. "blacklevel" =
attribute=20
  is defined as "Specifies the image brightness. Default is 0." What is =
the=20
  scale here? This needs to be defined. Is it 0-1.0, 0-255 or what? And =
what is=20
  "image brightness" in terms of the art? Is this luminosity? Opacity? =
Is this=20
  setting the level of the black point? For "cropleft", etc. -- what =
units are=20
  allowed? (implies %) How does "detectmouseclick" work when no event =
model is=20
  defined? "emboss effect" is not defined. "gain" has the same problem =
as=20
  "blacklevel" -- no scale is defined. This element has two different id =

  attributes in two different namespaces, with two different types. =
"movie"=20
  attribute is described as "Specifies a pointer to a movie image. This =
is a=20
  data block that contains a pointer to a pointer to movie data". Excuse =
me? "A=20
  pointer to a pointer to movie data"? This is useless. The =
"recolortarget"=20
  example appears to contradict the description. It shows shows blue =
recolored=20
  to red, not black. The "src" attribute is said to be a URL, yet is =
typed to=20
  xsd:string. This should be xsd:anyURI.
  <LI>Page 1431, Section 2.15.3.30 =E2=80=94 no errors noted<BR>
  <LI>Page 3405, Section 5.1.5.2.7 =E2=80=94 The conflict resolution =
algorithm should be=20
  normative, not merely in a note.<BR>
  <LI>Page 875, Section 2.11.21 =E2=80=94 Instead of saying that the =
footnote "pos"=20
  element should be ignored if present at the section level, the schema =
should=20
  be defined so as to not allow it at the section level. In other words, =
this=20
  should be expressed as a syntax constraint.<BR>
  <LI>Page 1955, Section 3.3.1.20 =E2=80=94 This facility for adding =
"arbitrary" binary=20
  data to spreadsheets is said to be for "legacy third-party document=20
  components". No documentation or mapping for such legacy components =
has been=20
  provided, so interoperability with this legacy data cannot be =
achieved. Why=20
  isn't this expressed using the extension mechanisms of Part 5 of the =
DIS?<BR>
  <LI>Page 4526, Section 6.1.2.13 =E2=80=94 The "allowoverlap" attribute =
is not=20
  sufficiently defined. In particular, what determines whether the =
object shifts=20
  to right or left? ST_BWMode is not adequately defined. For example, =
one option=20
  is "Use light shades of gray only". How light? And what is the =
difference=20
  between "hide" and "undrawn"? Also, concept of "wrapping polygon" is =
not=20
  sufficiently defined. For example, what is the wrapping polygon for an =
oval?=20
  The purpose of "dgmlayoutmru" is obscure. Wouldn't the =
most-recently-used=20
  layout option be the one which is actually in use, "dgmlayout"? The=20
  "dgmnodekind" attribute is undefined, said to be =
"application-specific". Is=20
  interoperabilty not allowed? The text seems to imply that applications =
must=20
  use application-specific values. The "href" attribute is give a string =
schema=20
  type. Shouldn't this be xsd:anyURI. The "id" attribute is said to be a =
"unique=20
  identifier". Unique in what domain? Among shapes of this type? Among =
all=20
  shapes? All shapes on this page? Among all ID's in the document? The=20
  "preferrelative" attribute is not sufficiently defined. Where is the =
original=20
  size stored? After what reformatting? This appears to be a =
specification for=20
  runtime behavior, not a storage artifact. But it is not clear what is=20
  required. For the "regroupid", where is the list of these possible =
id's? The=20
  Hyperlink targets _media and _search are Internet Explorer proprietary =

  features.
  <LI>Page 1193, Section 2.15.1.39 =E2=80=94 no errors noted<BR>
  <LI>Page 1459, Section 2.15.3.46 =E2=80=94 no errors noted
  <LI>Page 2671, Section 3.17.7.150 =E2=80=94 no errors noted
  <LI>Page 2347, Section 3.10.1.69 =E2=80=94 An "AutoShow" filter is not =
defined in this=20
  standard, though it is called for in several places of this section. =
"Average"=20
  aggregation function is not defined. In fact, none of these =
aggregation=20
  functions are defined. Although some have common mathematical =
definitions, in=20
  a spreadsheet context it is critical to make an explicit statement on=20
  treatment of strings, blanks, empty cells, etc. For dataSourceSort, =
what type=20
  of sort is required? Lexical or locale-sensitive? This element seems =
to mix=20
  field-specific settings, like dragToCol with pivotTable-wide settings =
like=20
  hiddenLevel. This will result in large data redundancy as settings =
like=20
  hiddenLevel are stored multiple times, once for each pivotField. =
"Inclusive=20
  Mode" is not defined. "Measure based filter" is not defined. =
"AutoSort" mode=20
  is not defined. The resolution of pivot table versus cell styles is =
ambiguous.=20
  "If the two formats differ, the cell-level formatting takes =
precedence." Is=20
  this negotiation done at the level of the entire text style? Style ID? =
Or at=20
  the attribute level? "Outline form" is not defined. "server-based page =
field"=20
  is not defined. (what is a page field?) "member caption" is undefined.
  <LI>Page 2885, Section 3.18.51 =E2=80=94 The values of the given type =
(ST_OleUpdate)=20
  are explicitly tied to the Microsoft Windows OLE2 technology via the =
two=20
  method calls IOleObject::Update or IOleLink::Update
  <LI>Page 3951, Section 5.5.3.4 =E2=80=94 The base values "margin" and =
"edge" are=20
  ambiguous. Is it specifying positioning from the left or right page =
edge?
  <LI>Page 2710, Section 3.17.7.200 =E2=80=94 The description of =
"lookup-vector" is=20
  insufficient. It seems to be saying that the range should be sorted. =
Is this=20
  really correct? Spreadsheet functions typically do not have side =
effects.=20
  Also, the sorting procedure is explicitly defined only defined for the =
Latin=20
  alphabet. What about the rest of allowed Unicode characters, including =
the C0=20
  control characters which are allowed in SpreadsheetML cell contents? =
Where are=20
  they sorted?<BR>
  <LI>Page 934, Section 2.13.5.5 =E2=80=94 The "id" attribute is =
required to be unique,=20
  but it is not specified over what domain it must be unique.
  <LI>Page 607, Section 2.6.2 =E2=80=94 What does "reversing the =
borders's appearance=20
  mean"? How much offset is required for a shadow?=20
  <LI>Page 201, Section 2.3.2.19 =E2=80=94 This feature allows the =
suppressing of both=20
  spell and grammar checking for a text run. These should be two =
different=20
  settings, one for spelling and one for grammar proofing. There are =
many cases=20
  where it is important to check one, but not the other, just as in =
content=20
  comprised of sentence fragments, which are not grammatically complete, =
but=20
  where correct spelling is desired.
  <LI>Page 1240, Section 2.15.1.74 =E2=80=94 This setting specifies that =
the document=20
  should be saved into an undefined invalid XML format. But it is not =
stated how=20
  an XSLT transfor can be applied to an OOXML document, since OOXML is a =
Zip=20
  file containing many XML documents. So what exactly is the specified =
XSLT=20
  applied to?<BR></LI></OL><BR>That's as far as I've gone. But this =
doesn't look=20
good, does it? Not only am I finding numerous errors, these errors =
appear to be=20
new ones, ones not detected by the NB 5-month review, and as such were =
not=20
addressed in Geneva. Since I have not come across any error that =
actually was=20
fixed at the BRM, the current estimate of the defect removal =
effectiveness of=20
the Fast Track process is &lt; 1/64 or 1.5%. That is the upper bounds.=20
(Confidence interval? I'll need to check on this, but I'm thinking this =
would be=20
based on standard error of a proportion, where SE=3Dsqrt((p*(1-p))/N)), =
making our=20
confidence interval 1.5% =C2=B1 3%) Of course, this value will need to =
be adjusted as=20
my study continues. However, it is starting to look like the Fast Track =
review=20
was very shallow and that detected only a small percentage of the errors =
in the=20
DIS.<BR><BR>[20 March Update]<BR><BR>As one commenter noted, the page =
numbers=20
I'm using above are PDF page numbers, not the page numbers on bottom of =
each=20
page. If I used the printed pages then I would need to deal with all the =
Roman=20
numeral front matter pages as an exception. Simpler to just use the one =
large=20
domain of PDF page numbers.<BR><BR>PDF Page Number =3D Printed Page =
Number +=20
7<BR><BR>I will continue to report new defects, according to the =
original random=20
number list I generated. I'll update the statistics every =
25.<BR><BR>Here's some=20
more for today:<BR><BR>
<OL start=3D26>
  <LI>Page 4192, Section 5.8.2.20 =E2=80=94 "fPublished" attribute is =
defined as=20
  "Specifies whether the shape shall be published with the worksheet =
when sent=20
  to the spreadsheet server. This is for use when interfacing with a =
document=20
  server." What worksheet? This section is in the DrawingML reference =
material.=20
  Charts could appear in presentations as well. This should not be =
limited to=20
  worksheets. Also what is a "spreadsheet server"? No such technology =
has been=20
  defined in this standard. Also no protocol has been defined for =
publishing to=20
  a spreadsheet server. Is this some proprietary hook for SharePoint? =
The=20
  "macro" attribute allows the storage of application-defined scripts. =
We are=20
  told that the macro "should be ignored if not understood." However =
there is no=20
  mechanism for determining what language the script is in. How do we =
know if we=20
  understand the macro? Content sniffing? Attempt to execute it and see =
if we=20
  get a runtime error? But by that time, once we find out that we do not =

  understand it, it is too late to ignore the macro. We may have already =

  triggered runtime side effects. What we really need here is some way =
to=20
  declare what scripting language is being used, via a namespace or an=20
  additional attribute like "lang".
  <LI>Page 3526, Section 5.1.5.4.21 =E2=80=94 The "algn" attribute =
specifies the text=20
  alignment. Allowed values include left, right, center, justified, etc. =

  However, what is lacking is "start" and "end" alignment, which are =
sensitive=20
  to writing direction and are part of internationalization bets =
practices, for=20
  example, XSL-FO. When translating a document between RTL and LTR =
systems, the=20
  approach used by OOXML will harder to deal with and be more expensive =
to=20
  translate, since the translator will need to manually play with styles =
on not=20
  just perform an semi-automated translation.<BR><BR></LI></OL><BR>[End=20
Update]<BR><BR>I'll continue to review the remaining 173 pages of my =
random=20
sample and update the numbers and the defect list as I go. If you want =
to play=20
along at home, the upcoming random page numbers will be:<BR><BR>
