<DIV class=3DblogComment><A name=3D6134330637640388900></A>Joining in =
the "find a=20
flaw" game with just one of your listed pages (from ECMA 376 part 4). =
(The=20
following has <I>not</I> been checked against BRM =
resolutions.)<BR><BR>p. 3997,=20
sec. 5.7.2.13-14:<BR><BR><I>5.7.2.13 bandFmt (Band Format) <BR>This =
element=20
specifies the formatting band of a surface chart. =
</I><BR><BR><I>5.7.2.14=20
bandFmts (Band Formats) This element contains a collection of formatting =
bands=20
for a surface chart indexed from low to high.</I><BR><BR>A "bandFmt" =
consists of=20
a index (idx) and a shape property (spPr, which defines things like fill =
pattern=20
and outline). However, nowhere is it clearly defined how an =
implementation is to=20
display a "surface chart" from a collection of "formatting =
bands".<BR><BR>In=20
particular, the "bandFmts" are used in both 5.7.2.204 (surface3Dchart) =
and=20
5.7.2.205 (surfacechart). In the latter (2d) case, I suppose one might =
guess=20
that the "band formats" are a sequence of shapes to be drawn, one on top =
of the=20
other, to form a 2d contour chart, but this is not specified explicitly. =
In the=20
former (3d) case, I have a much harder time trying to infer how the =
"formatting=20
bands" are to be drawn. From what perspective is the 3d chart drawn, for =

example...is a scene3d child element (5.1.4.1.26) required to be present =
in the=20
spPr in this case, and if not what is the default? Apparently not =
specified. And=20
what in the world should one do if different "formatting bands" of the =
same=20
chart have different scene3d children!? Even if a scene3d child is =
present, what=20
3d perspective (e.g. orthogonal projection?) is used? This is apparently =
set by=20
5.1.12.47 (preset camera type), but a cursory inspection of that section =
reveals=20
perspectives that are grossly underspecified, and seem to be each =
"defined"=20
largely by a single example image. (For example, "legacy oblique top" =
and=20
"perspective below" are hardly sufficient to define the precise viewing =
angles,=20
vanishing points, etcetera. Furthermore, wouldn't it be better to just =
define=20
those quantities numerically rather than have a finite number of =
underspecified=20
presets---compare, e.g., how OpenGL perspective cameras are defined by a =

position and 6 numbers---much less including "legacy" presets?) Or, for =
example,=20
what does the "wireframe" boolean attribute (which "specifies the =
surface chart=20
is drawn as wireframe", 5.7.2.231), really mean in terms of the visual=20
appearance of the chart? Not explained (and there are multiple =
reasonable ways=20
to draw 3d wireframes, e.g. as a set of disjoint 3d contour lines, or =
tesselated=20
into rectangles, or triangles, or...).<BR><BR>One could go on and =
on....it=20
doesn't seem possible for two implementations to display surface charts =
from the=20
same file, especially 3d surface charts, in the same way based only on =
this=20
specification, without referring to one another's =
implementation.<BR><BR>In=20
searching for information on "band formats", I found another apparent=20
goof:<BR><BR><I>5.7.2.144 pivotFmts (Pivot Formats) This element =
contains a=20
collection of formatting bands for a surface chart indexed from low to=20
high.</I><BR><BR>Except that "pivotFmts" aren't used in surface charts, =
they are=20
a child of "chart" (5.7.2.27), and contain a list of "pivotFmt" elements =
which=20
are a "set of formatting to be applied to the chart that is based on a=20
pivotTable" (5.7.2.143). So 5.7.2.144 seems to be misdescribed =
(copy-and-pasted=20
from 5.7.2.14?).<BR><BR>It's a horrifying exercise to go through the =
ECMA 376=20
document while pretending it will be your job to decipher and actually =
implement=20
these features. Even starting at a random page (3997, from Rob's list), =
one=20
finds a neverending chain of vagueness and slapdash =
engineering.<BR><BR>In=20
practice, it seems practically impossible for an implementer to proceed =
without=20
continually checking how MS Office interprets these Mycenaean =
scratchings.<BR>
