<DIV class=3DblogComment><A name=3D6564961079784304416></A>Another page =
from your=20
list: p. 5143, section 7.5.3.1 ST_Guid (128-bit GUID =
Value):<BR><BR><I>This=20
simple type specifies that its values shall be a 128-bit globally unique =

identifier (GUID) value.</I><BR><BR>It further states =
that:<BR><BR><I>This=20
simple type's contents must match the following regular expression =
pattern:=20
\{[0-9A-F]{8}-[0-9A-F]{4}-[0-9A-F]{4}-[0-9A-F]{4}-[0-9A-F]{12}\}.=20
</I><BR><BR>and they give the example=20
<I>{A67AC88A-A164-4ADE-8889-8826CE44DE6E}"</I><BR><BR>First problem: =
they don't=20
give any guidance regarding how to interpret this ST_Guid string as a =
"128-bit"=20
integer value. Presumably it is 32 hexadecimal digits, but the =
implementor=20
should not need to guess, nor is the byte order indicated. [And =
elsewhere in the=20
standard, GUID values are manipulated using integer arithmetic, e.g. in =
section=20
2.8.1 (Font Embedding) it requires you to "reverse the order of the =
bytes" of a=20
GUID and "XOR the value" with something.]<BR><BR>Second problem: the =
GUID=20
"shall" be a "globally unique identifier," but what does it mean to be =
"globally=20
unique?" Does the implementation have to require that the identifier is =
unique=20
within the document, within all OOXML documents on the user's hard disk, =
or all=20
OOXML documents in the globe? No explanation is given anywhere, nor is =
any=20
algorithm to generate GUIDs described.<BR><BR><A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Globally_Unique_Identifier"=20
rel=3Dnofollow>According to Wikipedia</A>, "GUID" is a Microsoft =
terminology for a=20
specific space of 128-bit identifiers (and specific bit patterns are =
reserved=20
for use in various Microsoft protocols), and is generated by specific =
algorithms=20
(some of which apparently create serious privacy problems). Presumably, =
some=20
version of Microsoft's GUID "standard" is what is intended for ST_Guid, =
but as=20
far as I can tell this is never explicitly indicated.<BR><BR>In short, =
OOXML=20
needs to define what precisely is meant by a "GUID" and how they are to =
be=20
generated.<BR><BR>Furthermore, ST_Guid is not used consistently =
throughout Ecma=20
376. In section 7.6.2.30 (Guid), it defines b:Guid element that =
"specifies the=20
GUID of a source" and uses the same format as ST_Guid in the example, =
but is=20
stored as the "ST_String255 simple type". OOXML also defines a ST_Clsid =
(Class=20
ID simple type, sec. 7.4.3.2), which stores a GUID with exactly the same =
format=20
definition as ST_Guid---why not use ST_Guid for class IDs, =
then?<BR><BR>I=20
searched the proposed BRM resolutions and couldn't find anything on this =
issue.=20
(I think. Rob, can you provide a link to a PDF of all the BRM =
resolutions? I'm=20
not sure I'm searching the right thing for the BRM.)<BR>
